evailing view of therapeutic culture as a destructive force that encourages narcissism, insecurity, and social isolation. The collection encourages us to examine what legitimate needs therapeutic practices have served and what unexpected political and social functions they may have performed. Offering both an extended history and a series of critical interventions organized around keywords like pain, privacy, and narcissism, this volume offers a more nuanced, empirically grounded picture of therapeutic culture than the one popularized by critics. Rethinking Therapeutic Culture is a timely book that will change the way we’ve been taught to see the landscape of therapy and self-help.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSelf-help groups. 0aTherapeutic communities. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  atherapy, self help, narcissism, first world problems, political correctness, pain, suffering, oprah, emotions, big pharma, mental health, illness, psychology, millennials, insecurity, isolation, trauma, privacy, gospel, religion, faith, hope, belief, guru, freedom, spirituality, race, class, harlem, discrimination, prejudice, other, motherhood, maternity, feminism, gender, sexuality, taboo, kink, deviance, confessional magazines, shame, secrets, identity, drugs, prescriptions, rehabilitation, prison, redemption, recovery, growth, nonfiction.1 aAhad, Badia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAubry, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBender, Courtney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBost, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErzen, Tanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabriel, Joseph M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb